{"text": "where \u03c0 = I/2. First verify that N is a quantum channel and then show by explicit calcula-\n\ntion that \u2225\u03c1 \u2212\u03c3\u22252 < \u2225N(\u03c1) \u2212N(\u03c3)\u22252 for this example. On the other hand, let \u03c1 = 0\u27e9\u27e80 ,\n\n\u03c3 = 1\u27e9\u27e81 , and N(\u03c9) =\n\n1\n\n2 (\u03c9 + X\u03c9X). Show that \u2225\u03c1 \u2212\u03c3\u22252 > \u2225N(\u03c1) \u2212N(\u03c3)\u22252 for this\n\nother example. Message: Do not use the Hilbert\u2013Schmidt distance as a measure of distin-\n\nguishability!\n\n9.7 History and Further Reading\n\nHolevo (1972) introduced and studied a function of two quantum states \u03c1 and \u03c3 that is very\n\nclosely related to the Uhlmann fidelity from Definition 9.2.3 and Theorem 9.2.1:\n\nFH(\u03c1, \u03c3) \u2261\n\n\u0002\n\nTr{\u221a\u03c1\u221a\u03c3}\n\n\u00032 .\n\n(9.249)\n\nThis function is now known as the Holevo fidelity and was rediscovered as \u201cquantum affinity\u201d\n\nby Luo and Zhang (2004). Holevo (1972) proved that FH(\u03c1, \u03c3) is related to the normalized\n\ntrace distance in the following way:\n\n1 \u2212\n\np\n\nFH(\u03c1, \u03c3) \u22641\n\n2 \u2225\u03c1 \u2212\u03c3\u22251 \u2264\n\np\n\n1 \u2212FH(\u03c1, \u03c3),\n\n(9.250)\n\nwhich is very similar to the inequalities presented in Theorem 9.3.1. In fact, by employing\n\nthe inequality FH(\u03c1, \u03c3) \u2264F(\u03c1, \u03c3), as well as (9.250) and Theorem 9.3.1, we conclude the\n\nfollowing generalization of Theorem 9.3.1:\n\n1 \u2212\n\np\n\nF(\u03c1, \u03c3) \u22641 \u2212\n\np\n\nFH(\u03c1, \u03c3) \u22641\n\n2 \u2225\u03c1 \u2212\u03c3\u22251 \u2264\n\np\n\n1 \u2212F(\u03c1, \u03c3) \u2264\n\np\n\n1 \u2212FH(\u03c1, \u03c3)\n\n(9.251)\n\nc\u20dd2019\n\nMark M. Wilde\u2014Licensed under a Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 3.0 Unported License\n\n286\n\nCHAPTER 9. DISTANCE MEASURES\n\nIn spite of these interesting relations and various properties that the Holevo fidelity FH\n\npossesses, 